{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="6000-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">Error 6000, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Error 6000 is the QuickBooks Desktop 6000-series &mdash; a whole family of company-file errors that all mean the same thing at the core: QuickBooks reached for your company file and couldn&rsquo;t open it. You almost always see the 6000 paired with a second number that narrows down why &mdash; 6000 -83, 6000 -301, 6000 -82, and others &mdash; but the family shares one symptom and one diagnostic approach. It most often appears when opening a file over a network, working in multi-user mode, restoring a backup, or after the file has been moved to a new computer or drive.</p>
      <p>The good news is that the 6000-series is highly fixable, and the self-fix steps below work in order of likelihood &mdash; running QuickBooks Tool Hub (Quick Fix my File, then File Doctor) resolves many 6000-series errors before deeper troubleshooting is needed. If self-fix doesn&rsquo;t resolve it, the error recurs within days, or it appears with a suffix that won&rsquo;t clear, a Certified ProAdvisor diagnostic identifies the deeper cause &mdash; typically network/hosting configuration or genuine company-file integrity damage past the documented surface steps. The 6000-series are QuickBooks Desktop and Enterprise errors; they do not appear in QuickBooks Online.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

